we introduce a
renormalized action

00:22:46.820 --> 00:22:52.195
which is defined by your
original action-- say,

00:22:52.195 --> 00:22:53.950
the [INAUDIBLE] action.

00:22:53.950 --> 00:22:55.670
But this is divergence.

00:22:55.670 --> 00:22:57.440
So we first need
to regularize it.

00:22:57.440 --> 00:23:00.270
So we normally do
regularization.

00:23:00.270 --> 00:23:03.300
So instead of
evaluating all the way

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:05.830
to z equal to 0, which
will be divergent,

00:23:05.830 --> 00:23:10.360
we cut it off at some
z equal to epsilon.

00:23:10.360 --> 00:23:13.430
So this is your full space time.

00:23:13.430 --> 00:23:15.580
So z equal to 0 is,
again, your boundary.

00:23:19.176 --> 00:23:21.050
So you integrate all
the way to z equal to 0.

00:23:21.050 --> 00:23:22.870
You will get a divergence.

00:23:22.870 --> 00:23:27.800
So we just cut it off at
a z equal to epsilon, OK?

00:23:30.620 --> 00:23:37.150
And then we added
the counterterm,

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:39.180
which can be expressed
in terms of the phi

00:23:39.180 --> 00:23:43.350
c evaluated at this epsilon, OK?

00:23:46.780 --> 00:23:49.590
And this [? displaced ?] row
should cancel the divergence

00:23:49.590 --> 00:23:52.640
here, OK?

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:54.050
Should cancel divergence here.

00:23:54.050 --> 00:23:56.900
But this St is
much-- so St should

00:23:56.900 --> 00:23:58.240
satisfy some simple criterion.

00:24:02.990 --> 00:24:08.430
In principle, this
St can be arbitrary,

00:24:08.430 --> 00:24:11.470
but should satisfy
some criterion.

00:24:11.470 --> 00:24:28.320
First, this must be local
functionals of phi c, OK?

00:24:33.970 --> 00:24:38.478
The reason it must be
local functionals of phi c

00:24:38.478 --> 00:24:41.685
is because this should come
from short distance physics.

00:24:44.500 --> 00:24:45.900
And short distance
physics is not

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:47.610
something we can
really control even

00:24:47.610 --> 00:24:49.091
in the renormalizable theories.

00:24:49.091 --> 00:24:50.590
Even in the
renormalizable theories,

00:24:50.590 --> 00:24:55.240
we just look at
the quantity which

00:24:55.240 --> 00:24:57.345
are insensitive to those
short distance physics.

00:25:00.810 --> 00:25:06.510
So the short distance physics,
not something we can control.

00:25:06.510 --> 00:25:08.890
But one important thing
about short distance physics

00:25:08.890 --> 00:25:14.900
is that they all must come
from a single point, OK?

00:25:14.900 --> 00:25:19.350
So it means the counterterm
you act must be local, OK?

00:25:19.350 --> 00:25:21.330
And of course must be
covariant, et cetera.

00:25:21.330 --> 00:25:25.700
So local, covariant-- satisfy
those basic conditions

00:25:25.700 --> 00:25:29.755
and the covariant, et cetera,
with all the right symmetry.

00:25:32.260 --> 00:25:34.890
Essentially, this is
the only condition

00:25:34.890 --> 00:25:38.194
those counterterms
should satisfy.

00:25:38.194 --> 00:25:40.110
And then you can just
choose your counterterms

00:25:40.110 --> 00:25:44.650
to cancel the divergent
terms here, OK?

00:25:44.650 --> 00:25:48.240
But now the key
thing is that this

00:25:48.240 --> 00:25:52.850
is different from just throwing
away the divergent term here.

00:25:52.850 --> 00:25:58.630
Because this counterterm also
contain some finite terms.

00:25:58.630 --> 00:26:01.720
So that's normally, in
the [INAUDIBLE] field

00:26:01.720 --> 00:26:04.110
series, that may change
the finite terms here.

00:26:04.110 --> 00:26:06.370
And those finite
terms are constrained

00:26:06.370 --> 00:26:08.200
by the locality
and the covariant

00:26:08.200 --> 00:26:09.620
and [? those ?] symmetries.

00:26:09.620 --> 00:26:13.200
And actually, there's no
ambiguity in them, OK?

00:26:13.200 --> 00:26:15.780
Even though the divergent
term, in some sense,

00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:16.730
there's ambiguity.

00:26:16.730 --> 00:26:18.880
But in the finite term,
there's no ambiguity.

00:26:18.880 --> 00:26:22.630
And so we will see an example
at the end of this class.

00:26:25.340 --> 00:26:28.870
OK, so we need to
renormalize them.

00:26:28.870 --> 00:26:32.670
And this is the criterion
to normalize it, OK?

00:26:32.670 --> 00:26:35.500
So once we have
renormalized it, then we

00:26:35.500 --> 00:26:38.980
can just obtain the
n-point function.

00:26:38.980 --> 00:26:50.460
So the general
n-point function--

00:26:50.460 --> 00:26:58.890
say, oy x1, on xn-- if you
look at this n-point function,

00:26:58.890 --> 00:27:01.340
so let's say
