00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:03.380
Let me just tell you one thing.

00:34:03.380 --> 00:34:07.960
So consider you have a, say,
classical mechanical system.

00:34:07.960 --> 00:34:12.969
So you move from t0 to t1, OK?

00:34:12.969 --> 00:34:14.550
And then suppose
you have already

00:34:14.550 --> 00:34:16.370
found your classical solution.

00:34:16.370 --> 00:34:20.730
So this is a
classical trajectory.

00:34:20.730 --> 00:34:24.780
And then suppose you evaluate
your classical action.

00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:33.060
Say so this is t0 to t1 dt,
all evaluated at Xc, Xc dot, et

00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:34.650
cetera, OK?

00:34:34.650 --> 00:34:38.040
Xc is already
classical solution.

00:34:38.040 --> 00:34:44.350
And so this function-- and
let's suppose that Xc at t0

00:34:44.350 --> 00:34:49.530
is equal to X0, Xc
at t1 equal to X1.

00:34:49.530 --> 00:34:55.260
So this is the initial
value and the final value

00:34:55.260 --> 00:34:56.940
of your trajectory, OK?

00:34:59.570 --> 00:35:03.970
And then-- so clearly, because
of this boundary condition,

00:35:03.970 --> 00:35:09.600
